    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It's possible that your tomato plants are experiencing a nutrient deficiency, which could be causing the yellowing leaves starting from the bottom. Potassium deficiency is a common one that can cause this symptom. Potassium is crucial for overall plant health, including the growth of strong stems and resistance to diseases. You could try adding a balanced, slow-release fertilizer to the soil, or using a potassium-rich fertilizer. Just make sure to follow the instructions on the label to avoid over-fertilizing, which could cause more harm than good. Keep an eye on your plants and see if they start to perk up after you've taken action. Good luck!",
